pare   Bunts  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bunts","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Bunz</b> (see   Bunce  ) or   Banz  .","English: variant of   Bunce  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Bunt","meanings":["English: from an unrecorded Middle English <i>bunt</i> ‘something swollen’, related to modern English <i>bunt</i> ‘swelling, bag-like end of a net or sail’, and to Middle English <i>bunting</i> ‘small bird, corn bunting’. The name could have been a nickname given to a plump person. Derivation from Middle English <i>bonte</i>, <i>bunte</i> ‘sieve’ is formally also possible but less likely.","English: alternatively, from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Bunt(e)</i>, Old English <i>Bunt(a)</i>, perhaps derived from the same sense as in 1 above.","Dutch (mainly <b>Van de Bunt</b>): habitational name for someone who lived at a place called after its vegetation, which consisted of bunt grass, i.e. a meadow with tufts of a tough kind of grass."]},{"name":"Bones","meanings":["English: variant of   Bunce   1.","Irish: translation into English of Gaelic <b>Ó Cnáimhsighe</b>, by association with <i>cnámh</i> ‘bone’. Compare   Bonar   2.","Norwegian: habitational name from the farm name Bones in the province of Trøndelag. The first element is derived from the river name Bua, from Old Norse <i>búa</i> ‘live’, perhaps meaning ‘river that runs through a settled valley’. The second element is <i>nes</i> ‘promontory, headland’. Compare   Boness   and   Bonnes  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705210,"age":8,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705212,"age":28,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705213,"age":50,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mr. Bunce was born about 1592, in England. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1592–":"umbes 1592–Surnud","1615–1683":"1615–1683","1617–Male":"1617–Surnud","1592–Male":"1592–Surnud","1600":"1600","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1651":"1651","1683":"1683","1592":"1592","1617":"1617","about 1592":"umbes 1592","1615":"1615","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1592–":"noin 1592–Kuollut","1615–1683":"1615–1683","1617–Male":"1617–Kuollut","1592–Male":"1592–Kuollut","1600":"1600","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1651":"1651","1683":"1683","1592":"1592","1617":"1617","about 1592":"noin 1592","1615":"1615","England":"England"},"fr":{"